  "prompt": "How can you determine the variable cost ratio formula?",
  "response": "The variable cost ratio (also known as the variable cost to sales ratio) is calculated by dividing total variable costs by total sales revenue. Here's the formula and steps to determine it:\n\nFormula: Variable Cost Ratio = Total Variable Costs \u00f7 Total Sales Revenue\n\nSteps to calculate:\n1. Identify total variable costs for a specific period\n2. Identify total sales revenue for the same period\n3. Divide total variable costs by total sales revenue\n4. Express the result as a decimal or percentage\n\nExample:\n- Total Variable Costs = $60,000\n- Total Sales Revenue = $100,000\n- Variable Cost Ratio = $60,000 \u00f7 $100,000 = 0.60 or 60%\n\nSignificance:\n- Shows the proportion of sales revenue consumed by variable costs\n- Helps assess cost structure and profitability\n- Useful for break-even analysis and pricing decisions\n- Lower ratio indicates higher profit potential\n\nThe variable cost ratio can help managers understand how changes in sales volume impact total costs and potential profitability.",
